{"title_page": "\u00a1Tr\u00e9!", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Other uses|TRE (disambiguation){{!}}TRE}}Rapper Tre Moneybaby is a Detroit teenage rapper. His real name is Trevion R. Ward but most of you may know him as Tre, or Moneybaby . Tre Moneybaby is 16 years old, born November 29th 2003. He started rapping when he was just 3 years old but started taking it serious when he was 13 when he was under Detroit native Kelo Yay\u2019s wing and \u201cSafebin Ballaz ent.\u201d When the released songs featuring Tre Moneybaby such as , \u201cLookin like money\u201d \u201cWhat it cost\u201d \u201cWe can do it\u201d \u201cMillionaire Mindset\u201d and \u201cFatcs\u201d. After a year and a half they stopped working and all went their separate ways. Tre Moneybaby started releasing music on his own with another local rapper known as Paidd Kj under Blockbrothas ent. 2019 Tre Moneybaby had gotten plenty of exposure when he recorded a song called \u201cNever\u201d with Veeze and Detroit native Babyface Ray, even before that he had songs with artist such as, lil beno, baby drego, rocky badd and etc that\u2019s unreleased. September of 2019 he lost his mother but that did not hold him from chasing any of his dreams. February of 2020 he released a E.P called \u201cWritten Dreams\u201d  and music video \u201cHorse Power\u201d that\u2019s really a Detroit hellcat and scatpack type of turn up song. Even tho he is 16 and an local artist I did a bit of research and his name holds a little wait through certain parts of the city. As an upcoming artist Moneybaby\u2019s net worth is estimated at around $60,000-80,000 dollars.\n\n==Recording and release==\nOn April 11, 2012, Green Day announced that they would be releasing a trilogy of albums titled ''\u00a1Uno!'', ''\u00a1Dos!'', and ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' and stated that they would be released on September 25, 2012, November 13, 2012, and January 15, 2013, respectively, through Reprise Records.<ref name=\"prrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1682949/green-day-uno-dos-tres-albums.jhtml|title=Green Day Recording a Trilogy of Albums|work=MTV News|publisher=MTV Networks|first=Katie|last=Byrne|date=April 11, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a386556/green-day-confirm-new-albums-uno-dos-tre-release-dates.html|title=Green Day confirm new albums '\u00a1Uno! \u00a1Dos! \u00a1Tr\u00e9!' release dates|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]]|first=Lewis|last=Corner|date=June 11, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> On August 22, Armstrong gave preview of some songs through his [[iPhone]] on Zane Lowe's show on BBC Radio 1 in the UK. The preview included a brief snippet of \"8th Ave Serenade\". The track listing for ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' was revealed at the beginning of their video for the promotional single \"Nuclear Family\" from ''\u00a1Uno!''<ref name=\"nuclear family video\">{{cite AV media|people=Green Day|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jHmSyGjf6BA|title=\"Nuclear Family\" Video|date =12 September 2012|accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref> It was later released officially on the \"Idiot Club\" and was later posted on their website.<ref name=\"greenday1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenday.com/news/check-out-track-listing-tre-87751 |title=CHECK OUT THE TRACK LISTING FOR \u00a1TRE! \u2013 Green Day Official News |website=Greenday.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-24}}</ref> The song \"99 Revolutions\" previously appeared in the film ''[[The Campaign (film)|The Campaign]]''. \"99 Revolutions\" also appeared in a trailer released by Green Day on their YouTube channel on June 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZrQsT4JuSkc |title=Green Day: \u00a1Tr\u00e9! \u2013 coming 1/15 Official Trailer With Album Cover |website=YouTube |date=2012-06-21 |accessdate=2012-09-28}}</ref> On October 29, it was announced that the album's release will be pushed forward to December 11, 2012, due to Green Day having to cancel their upcoming 2012 section of their 2012/2013 tour and delay much of the 2013 leg.<ref name=\"NewReleaseDate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenday.com/news/press-release-92506 |title=PRESS RELEASE \u2013 Green Day Official News |website=Greenday.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-29}}</ref> On November 1, Green Day released \"Behind The Scenes of ''\u00a1Uno!'', ''\u00a1Dos!'', and ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' \u2013 Part 1\" which featured the preview of the song \"X-Kid\". The release date of the ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' LPs were pushed back to February 12, 2013, presumably to correct the erroneous inclusion of \"[[Stray Heart]]\" on initial pressings of the album, replacing the track with \"Drama Queen\", as present on CD and digital releases of the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boards.vinylcollective.com/index.php?/topic/80773-green-day-dos-aqua-blue-vinyl-exclusive-to-hot-topic/page__st__180 |title=Green Day \u2013 Dos aqua blue vinyl exclusive to Hot Topic \u2013 Page 10 \u2013 Vinyl Collective Message Board \u2013 Vinyl Collective \u2013 Page 10 |website=Boards.vinylcollective.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> Previews of \"Missing You\" and \"Dirty Rotten Bastards\" were featured on Green Day's ''[[\u00a1Cuatro!]]'' documentary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendaycommunity.org/topic/90990-drama-queen-leak-vinyl-false-pressing/page__st__30 |title=Drama Queen leak (Vinyl false pressing) \u2013 Page 2 \u2013 Green Day Chat \u2013 Green Day Community \u2013 Page 2 |website=Green Day Community |date= |accessdate=2012-11-17}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\nThe band released a video of a [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] tape playing for the song \"X-Kid\" and later confirmed it as the first single released on February 12, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases |title=Future Releases on Alternative Radio Stations, Independent Artist Song Releases &#124; |website=Allaccess.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==Music and composition==\nBillie Joe Armstrong had said the following about the trilogy: Each of the three albums has a totally different vibe. \"The first one is power pop. The second is more garage-y, ''Nuggets''-type rock. And the third is supposed to be epic. With the first album you're getting in the mood to party. On the second one, you're at the party. And the third album you're cleaning up the mess.\"<ref name=\"rollingstone2\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/premiere-green-days-power-pop-new-single-oh-love-20120716 |title=New and Hot Video: Premiere: Green Day's 'Power-Pop' New Single, 'Oh Love' |work=Rolling Stone |date=2012-07-16 |accessdate=2012-10-24}}</ref> ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' will be geared more towards stadium rock and will have more of a grandiose sound complete with string arrangements and brass sections. He also went on to say that the mood of ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' will be \"reflective\" and explained the album would be a \"mixed bag\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/interview-green-days-billie-joe-armstrong-uno-dos-and-tre |title=Interview: Green Day's Billie Joe Armstrong on '\u00a1Uno!,' '\u00a1Dos!' and '\u00a1Tre!' |website=Guitar World |date=2012-11-12 |accessdate=2012-11-20}}</ref> with the sound fluctuating from the punk rock feel of ''[[Dookie]]'' and ''[[Insomniac (Green Day album)|Insomniac]]'', the experimental elements of ''[[Nimrod (album)|Nimrod]]'' and ''[[Warning (Green Day album)|Warning]]'' and finishing with the stadium rock/rock opera sound taken from ''[[American Idiot]]'' and ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]''. While musically, Rob Cavallo said that \"They wanted to return to the simplicity of ''Dookie''.\" \"We also wanted to go pre-''Dookie'', back to our love of Fifties and Sixties music, close-to-the-bone [[rock and roll]]. You don't hear a gazillion parts. The majority of this is drums, bass, two guitars and vocals.\"<ref name=\"rollingstone2\"/> Frontman Billie Joe also stated that ''\u00a1Tre!'' would be the most ambitious album of the trilogy. He has also stated the following of the album's opening track: \"Brutal Love\", which marries [[glam rock]], [[doo-wop]] and [[soul music]], includes swelling strings at its conclusion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greendayauthority.com/news/3664/ |title=Track listing for \u00a1Tr\u00e9! has been released |website=Greendayauthority.com |date=2012-10-15 |accessdate=2012-10-24}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 64/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/%C2%A1tr%C3%A9!-mw0002491285 |title=\u00a1Tr\u00e9! \u2013 Green Day : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = C+<ref name=\"Heller\">{{cite news|last=Heller|first=Jason|date=December 11, 2012|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/green-day-tre,89741/|title=Green Day: \u00a1Tre!|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|location=Chicago|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|author=Ray Rahman |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20653693,00.html |title=Tre! \u2013 review \u2013 Green Day Review &#124; Music Reviews and News |website=EW.com |date=2012-07-19 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Hann\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Price\">{{cite news|last=Price|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Price|date=December 9, 2012|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/ios-album-review-green-day-tre-reprise-8395751.html|title=IoS album review: Green Day, Tre! (Reprise)|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London|accessdate=December 12, 2012|quote=...more typical is the Costello-esque pop-punk...}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref name=\"Nicolson\">{{cite journal|last=Nicolson|first=Barry|date=December 7, 2012|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/green-day/13921|title=Green Day \u2013 '\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'|journal=[[NME]]|location=London|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev7Score = 5/10<ref name=\"Ramirez\">{{cite web|last=Ramirez|first=AJ|date=December 11, 2012|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/166300-green-day-tre/|title=Green Day: \u00a1Tr\u00e9!|website=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|author=Anthony DeCurtis |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/tre-20121206 |title=Tre &#124; Album Reviews |work=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref>\n| rev9 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev9Score = {{rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/green-day-tre/2946 |title=Green Day: Tre &#124; Music Review |work=Slant Magazine |date= |accessdate=2012-12-11}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10Score = 6/10<ref name=\"Benson\">{{cite journal|last=Benson|first=Stephanie|date=December 13, 2012|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/green-day-tre-reprise-trilogy|title=Green Day, '\u00a1Tre!' (Reprise)|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|accessdate=December 18, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 64, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\", based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/tre!/green-day |title=Tre! Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More |website=Metacritic |date=2012-12-05 |accessdate=2012-12-23}}</ref> Ray Rahman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that the album \"lets their tightly wound [[hook (music)|hooks]] decompress, delivering stadium-worthy three-chord nods to various ghosts of rock past\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> [[AllMusic]] editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] felt that the album is \"hookier and not as ponderous as ''\u00a1Uno!'' but not quite as breakneck as ''\u00a1Dos!''\", writing that it \"feels like ... a collection of songs capturing the band at its loosest and poppiest, throwing away tunes without much care.\"<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> ''[[Kerrang!]]'' cited it as \"the best of the bunch\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: \u00a1Tr\u00e9!|journal=[[Kerrang!]]|location=London|date=December 8, 2012|page=50}}</ref> Although he found it to be \"littered with head-scratching filler and awkward sonic diversions\", Ryan Reed of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' called ''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' \"more raw, pointed and hard-hitting than anything they've released in years\".<ref name=\"Reed\">{{cite journal|last=Reed|first=Ryan|date=December 11, 2012|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/12/green-day-tre.html|title=Green Day: Tre!|journal=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|location=Decatur|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMichael Hann of ''[[The Guardian]]'' felt that \"it's got some pretty good songs \u2013 but they never get better than pretty good.\"<ref name=\"Hann\">{{cite news|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=January 3, 2013|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/03/green-day-tre-review|title=Green Day: \u00a1Tr\u00e9! \u2013 review|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|at=section G2, p. 24|accessdate=January 13, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' commented that the album \"feels scattershot and slapped together, making it difficult to enjoy on its own merits.\"<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|author=\"Amanda\" |url=http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/green_day_tre |title=Alternative Press &#124; Reviews &#124; Green Day \u2013 \u00a1Tr\u00e9! |website=Altpress.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref> Jason Heller of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' observed a lack of \"inspiration\" and wrote that the album \"succeeds most as an exercise in influence-dropping and self-recycling\".<ref name=\"Heller\"/> Barry Nicolson of ''[[NME]]'' viewed its songs as formulaic and found \"little to distinguish them\" from songs in the trilogy's first two albums.<ref name=\"Nicolson\"/> AJ Ramirez of [[PopMatters]] criticized its instrumentation as \"functional and characterless\", while critiquing the trilogy in general, \"The wide spread afforded by the ''\u00a1Uno!''/''\u00a1Dos!''/''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' trilogy does not suit a band whose aptitudes include simplicity, energy, and irreverence.\"<ref name=\"Ramirez\"/> Stephanie Benson at ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' stated \"''\u00a1Tr\u00e9!'' is not nearly the vivacious \"Let Yourself Go\"/\"Fuck Time\" party of its two predecessors. The music may be just as strong, tight, and impeccable \u2014 this is a band that's been going at it for more than a quarter of a century, after all \u2014 but there's a lightness missing here, a lack of passion.\" Benson also compared some of the songs to those on ''Dookie'' and ''Nimrod''.<ref name=\"Benson\"/>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe album debuted at number 13 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 58,000 copies in the United States. This became the second consecutive Green Day album, after ''[[\u00a1Dos!]]'', not to sell 100,000 records in its first week after signing to a major record label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481291/green-days-album-trilogy-what-happened-with-uno-dos-and-tre |title=Green Day's Album Trilogy: What Happened with 'Uno!,' 'Dos!' and 'Tre!'? |work=Billboard |date=2013-01-15 |accessdate=2013-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481312/bruno-mars-debuts-at-no-2-as-taylor-swifts-red-still-rules |title=Bruno Mars Debuts at No. 2 as Taylor Swift's 'Red' Still Rules |work=Billboard |date=2012-12-19 |accessdate=2013-04-05}}</ref> As of October 2016, the album had sold 155,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005091256/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases     |website=Hits Daily Double |title=Upcoming Releases|archivedate=October 5, 2016 |publisher=|accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> The album debuted at number 31 on the UK charts with first-week sales of 24,000 and total sales of 62,000 as of October 13, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzjack.com/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t194589.html|title=BuzzJack Music Forum|website=buzzjack.com}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics   = [[Billie Joe Armstrong]]\n| all_music    = [[Green Day]], except \"Brutal Love\", composed by Green Day and [[Sam Cooke]]\n| title1       = Brutal Love\n| length1      = 4:54\n| title2       = Missing You\n| length2      = 3:43\n| title3       = 8th Avenue Serenade\n| length3      = 2:36\n| title4       = Drama Queen\n| length4      = 3:07\n| title5       = [[X-Kid]]\n| length5      = 3:41\n| title6       = Sex, Drugs & Violence\n| length6      = 3:31\n| title7       = A Little Boy Named Train\n| length7      = 3:37\n| title8       = Amanda\n| length8      = 2:28\n| title9       = Walk Away\n| length9      = 3:45\n| title10      = Dirty Rotten Bastards\n| length10     = 6:26\n| title11      = 99 Revolutions\n| length11     = 3:49\n| title12      = [[The Forgotten (Green Day song)|The Forgotten]]\n| length12     = 4:58\n| total_length = 46:35\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed      = yes\n| headline       = Japan CD bonus tracks<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wmg.jp/artist/greenday/news_44565.html?rid=rss_44565 |title=\u3044\u3088\u3044\u3088\u4eca\u90313\u90e8\u4f5c\u306e\u6700\u7d42\u7ae0\u300e\u30c8\u30ec\uff01\u300f\u767a\u58f2\uff01\u3001\u9023\u52d5\u8cfc\u5165\u7279\u5178\u300e\u7206\u767a\u30e9\u30a4\u30f4\uff5e\u6e0b\u8c37\u7bc7\