ategory:Infrastructure in London]]\n[[Category:Port of London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the London Borough of Newham]]\n", "name_user": "Ehrenkater", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFuture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thames_Barrier"}
{"title_page": "Rafa\u0142 Malczewski", "text_new": "{{about||the snowboarder|Rafa\u0142 Skarbek-Malczewski}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish painter and mountaineer}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Rafa\u0142 Malczewski\n| image        = Jacek Malczewski - Portret syna Rafa\u0142a.jpg\n| image_size   = 250 px\n| caption      = [[Jacek Malczewski]]  Portrait of his son, Rafa\u0142\n| birth_date    = 24 October 1892\n| birth_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1965|02|15|1892|10|24|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Montreal]], [[Canada]]\n}}\n'''Rafa\u0142 Marceli Ludwik Fortunat J\u00f3zef Malczewski''' (24 October 1892 - 15 February 1965) was a Polish landscape and portrait painter, draughtsman, author and columnist. He was a noted [[Tatra Mountains|Tatra mountaineer]], [[Skiing in the Snow|skier]] and populariser of the [[Tatra Mountains]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his Tatra-themed painting |author=Lenartowicz, \u015awiatos\u0142aw|url=http://muzea.malopolska.pl/en/czy-wiesz-ze/-/a/o-rafale-malczewskim-i-jego-malarstwie-tatrzanskim?view=full|publisher=muzea.malopolska.pl|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Rafa\u0142 Malczewski - Kazimierz Sichulski.jpg|thumb|1923 Cartoon of Malczewski by [[Kazimierz Sichulski]]]]\n[[File:Zamar\u0142a Turnia.jpg|thumb|left|South face of ''Zamar\u0142a Turnia'' in the [[Tatra Mountains]]]]\nHe was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], four years after his sister, Julia, the son of Maria, n\u0117e Gralewska, and her husband the celebrated [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]] painter and professor of Fine Art, [[Jacek Malczewski]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416120803/http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-04-16 | title=Jacek Malczewski | publisher=Instytut Sztuki Polskiej Akademii Nauk. Culture.pl | work=Symbolizm w polskim malarstwie prze\u0142omu XIX i XX wieku | date=October 2002 | accessdate=October 17, 2012 | author=Kossowska, Irena | language=Polish}}</ref><ref name = \"IK\">{{cite web|author= Kossowska, Irena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski|date=2001|url= https://culture.pl/en/artist/rafal-malczewski|publisher=culture.pl|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> He graduated from the Saint Jacek High School in the city. From 1910\u20131915 he studied at the [[University of Vienna]]. He took courses in philosophy, architecture and [[agronomy]]. On his return to Krak\u00f3w he entered the [[Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts]], and was also apprenticed in his father's studio. In 1915 he began to travel frequently to [[Zakopane]] where he spent extensive periods, to climb, ski and paint, until the [[outbreak of World War II]]. He joined the local [[Mountain rescue]] team, [[Tatrza\u0144skie Ochotnicze Pogotowie Ratunkowe|TOPR]]. However in 1917 on the south face of \"Zamar\u0142a Turnia\" he and his climbing companion, Stanis\u0142aw Bronikowski, were caught in a climbing accident in which his friend died, while Malczewski clung to a hook all night awaiting rescue.\n\nIn October 1917 he married Bronis\u0142awa Dziadosz, an English teacher four years his senior and a [[US citizen]] of Polish descent who had immigrated into Poland. In November of the same year, their son Krzysztof was born. Despite an unhappy partnership, the couple went on to have a second child, Zofia. Their poor financial situation led to Rafa\u0142's artist father helping them out. In 1923 he bought for them a chalet called \"Marysin\".\n\nRafa\u0142 Malczewski was an associate and friend of a group of artists, musicians and intellectuals who would congregate in the [[Mountain resort]] of Zakopane in the early part of the 20th century. They included [[Stanis\u0142aw Ignacy Witkiewicz]], [[Karol Szymanowski]], [[Kornel Makuszy\u0144ski]], [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]. In 1932 he joined the \"Rhythm Association of artists (Stowarzyszenie Artyst\u00f3w Polskich \u201eRytm\u201d) and was a set designer for productions of [[Strindberg]] and [[Stanis\u0142aw Witkiewicz]] at the ''Formistyczny Theatre'' in Zakopane. In 1937 he was awarded the \"Wawrzyn Akademicki\" award from the [[Polska Akademia Literatury]] \"for services to Polish art\".<ref>Rocznik Polskiej Akademii Literatury 1937\u20131938, Warsaw 1939, p. 175.</ref> 1938 he donated part of his artistic output to the newly re-opened [[National Museum of Warsaw]] to which, several years earlier on account of his material difficulties, he had sold the entirety of his father's work left to him by Malczewski Sr.\n\n== Travels ==\n[[File:Rafal Malczewski Ottawa.jpg|thumb|Rafa\u0142 Malczewski in [[Ottawa]]. He settled in [[Canada]] in 1942]]\nIn 1939 after the [[outbreak of World War II]], having already abandoned his wife and children, he escaped over the [[Slovakia|Slovak]] border, with his partner Zofia Mikucka, and via [[Budapest]] and [[Venice]] made his way to [[Paris]]. There he fell on the generosity of the Polish embassy to help him out of another financial difficulty. In 1940 they travelled on to [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]], where they stayed for four months. At the beginning of 1941 they moved to [[Brazil]]. At first they stayed in [[Rio de Janeiro]] where he was able to sell some of his paintings which consisted of water colour landscapes of Rio, [[Curitiba]] and of [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Parana]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=CANADIAN ART CRITICS ON RAFA\u0141 MALCZEWSKI|author= Krzy\u017canowski, Jerzy R.|journal=The Polish Review|volume= 38, No. 2 |date=1993|pages=191-201}}</ref><ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\nIn 1942 they moved to Curitiba to stay with his cousin, Maria Bochdan-Niedenthal. Shortly after, he succeeded in obtaining Canadian visas for himself and his girlfriend, Zofia, to travel to [[Ottawa]]. By December 1942 he held his first Canadian exhibition in the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]. He managed to persuade the [[Canadian railways]] to sponsor him and Zofia to travel across [[Canada]] and the [[USA]] in search of artistic subjects in exchange for publicity scenery. He spent the winter of 1943 in the [[Rocky Mountains]], which led to a series of canvases that kept him supplied for many exhibitions until 1949. A stay in [[New York City|New York]] in 1950 was fruitful enough for further sales of his work. \n\nDespite developing problems with his sight, like his father before him, the ensuing years saw a great flowering of his painting and writing. After his wife, Bronislawa died in Warsaw in 1953, he finally married Zofia Mikucka.<ref>{{cite book|title=Coraz trudniej \u017cy\u0107, a umrze\u0107 strach, Listy 1952\u20131955|trans-title=It gets more difficult to live, but perish the thought of dying. Letters 1952-1955 |authors =  Malczewski, Zofia and Rafa\u0142, and [[Jan Lecho\u0144|Lecho\u0144, Jan]]|publisher=Biblioteka Wi\u0119zi|lang=pl|isbn=978-8-3603-5649-4}}\n</ref> A stroke in 1957 led to a partial paralysis which obliged him to give up painting in oils, but he was able to continue with water colours. He managed to obtain sponsorship from the CIA-controlled [[Radio Free Europe]] and from [[Quebec City]]. In 1959 the daughter of Zofia Malczewska-Kondracka invited him to visit Poland. Despite great nostalgia for the south of the country, he  resolved to remain in Canada, but his journey was described in his memoir, ''Wspomnieniach z Polski'' and serialised in the [[London]] \u00e9migr\u00e9 paper, [[Wiadomo\u015bci (London magazine)|Wiadomo\u015bci]]. From 1961 he was kept by his daughter, Zofia, and three years later, in 1964 his last exhibition took place in [[Montreal]]. He died and was buried there in 1965.<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\n== Characteristics of his art ==\nMagdalena Ma\u0142etko has emphasised several pointers to understand Malczewski's art. His successful artist father wished him to have a more reliable career than his own. While at the University of Vienna Malczewski studied [[Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]] as part of the philosophy course, but he failed to complete his degree. He never got over the death of his close friend and climbing partner Bronikowski, who died on a climb they did together in 1917. His first marriage was an attempt to get over his grief and was loveless, and more of a duty due to Bronis\u0142awa's pregnancy. Painting came to him instinctually as he watched his prolific father working in his studio. Malczewski was an artist difficult to categorise, although he developed his own distinctive style. This has been called \"hyper realism\" (Witkacy) and \"naive\". His themes were predominantly empty vistas, mountain scenery, snowscapes and glassy lakes. He also did portraits, cartoons and a series of rally cars and industrial scenery in [[Silesia]]. The great hiatus of his life was leaving his family and his beloved Zakopane in 1939. Three years later he had settled in Canada having travelled through Southern Europe and Brazil, where his palette responded to the colour and light. His later life was a struggle with increasing blindness and paralysis which allowed him only to use water colour, alongside his writing, which he managed to do until his death.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ma\u0142etko, Magdalena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i jego widzenie nowoczesno\u015bci|date=2009   |url=https://www.kul.pl/files/564/public/ARTykuly/ARTykuly002/ARTykuly_nr002_2009_MM_s22.pdf|lang=pl|publisher=www.kul.pl|access-date=2020-04-14|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his vision of modernity}}</ref>\n\n== Selected exhibitions and awards==\nMalczewski's first public show was with [[Witkacy]] at Garlinski's Salon in Warsaw in 1924.<ref name = \"IK\"/> Solo shows followed in:\n* Zakopane (1926)\n* Warsaw (1928, 1929, 1935, 1938)\n* Krak\u00f3w (1930, 1932) \n* [[Lodz|\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] (1935)\n* [[Katowice]] (1938) \n* Montreal Museum of Arts ( 1942)\n* Dominion Gallery (1949)  \n* Corcoran Gallery, [[Washington, D.C.]] (1944).<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\nAs a member of the Society for the Propagation of Polish Art Abroad, he participated in the following group exhibitions:\n* [[Prague]] and [[Helsinki]] (1929)\n* Vienna and Paris (1928) \n* [[Brussels]] and [[The Hague]] (1929)\n* Budapest and [[Copenhagen]] (1930)\n* Venice (13th Biennale) and [[Los Angeles]] (1932)\n* [[Moscow]], [[Edinburgh]], and [[San Francisco]] (1933)\n* New York (1933)\n* [[Berlin]] (1936)\n* [[Pittsburgh]] (1938)\n* [[Ottawa]] (1942)\n* [[Detroit]] (1945) \n* [[Montreal]] (1954). \nAmong the many awards he received were:\n* President [[Ignacy Mo\u015bcicki]] prize 1930\n* Golden laurel of ''Polska Akademia Literatury'' 1937\n* Gold Medal for his ''Wiosna w g\u00f3rach'' [\"Spring in the mountains\"] at the Paris [[Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne]] 1937\n* ''The Visual Arts Prize'' of Paris-based Polish-language monthly, ''[[Kultura]]'' 1962.<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\n== Selected written work ==\nIn his writing Rafa\u0142 Malczewski evoked the atmosphere of [[Interbellum Poland|interbellum]] Zakopane:\n* ''Od cepra do wariata'', [From Lowland Dweller to Madman]\n* ''Narkotyk g\u00f3r. Nowele tatrza\u0144skie'', [\"Addicted to mountains. Tatran novellas\"] (1928)\n* ''Tatry i Podhale'' [\"The Tatras and their Foothills\"] (1935)\n* ''G\u00f3ry wo\u0142aj\u0105'' [\"The Mountains Beckon\"] (1939).<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n* ''P\u0119pek \u015bwiata. Wspomnienia z Zakopanego'', [\"The Navel of the World. Memories of Zakopane\"].<ref>{{cite book|author=Malczewski, Rafa\u0142|title=P\u0119pek \u015bwiata. Wspomnienia z Zakopanego|date=1960|publisher= Wydawnictwo LTW|url=http://www.lubimyczytac.pl/ksiazka/87425/pepek-swiata-wspomnienia-z-zakopanego|lang=pl}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Folga-Januszewska, Dorota|title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i Mit Zakopanego|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and the Myth of Zakopane|lang=pl|publisher=Bosz|date=2006|volume=1|isbn=978-8-3897-4734-1}}\n* {{cite book|author=Folga-Januszewska, Dorota|title=Zakopane w czasach Rafa\u0142a Malczewskiego|editor=Jab\u0142o\u0144ska, Teresa|trans-title=Zakopane in the Times of Rafa\u0142 Malczewski|lang=pl|publisher=Bosz|date=2006|volume=2|isbn=978-8-3897-4734-1}}\n* {{cite web|author=Ma\u0142etko, Magdalena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i jego widzenie nowoczesno\u015bci|date=2009   |url=https://www.kul.pl/files/564/public/ARTykuly/ARTykuly002/ARTykuly_nr002_2009_MM_s22.pdf|lang=pl|publisher=www.kul.pl Art History Students magazine, [[Catholic University of Lublin]]|access-date=2020-04-14|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his vision of modernity}}\n* {{cite web|author=Szymalak-Bugajska, Paulina|date=2017|url=https://niezlasztuka.net/o-sztuce/jacek-malczewski-rycerz-polskiej-sztuki/|title=Jacek Malczewski \u2013 rycerz polskiej sztuki|trans-title=Jacek Malczewski - Knight of Polish Art|lang=pl|publisher=niezlasztuka.net|access-date=2020-04-14}} Contains illustrations and quotes from Malczewski family, including Rafa\u0142.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_R/Index.htm Paintings by Rafa\u0142 Malczewski]\n* [https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/aac-aic/artiste_detailler_bas-artist_detail_bas.app?rID=10818&fID=2&lang=en&qlang=en&pID=672&ps=50&sort=AM_ASC& Artists in Canada - Canadian Government entry]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malczewski, Rafa\u0142}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Polish painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Polish landscape painters]]\n[[Category:Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Zakopane]]\n[[Category:Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:People from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Polish mountain climbers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the snowboarder|Rafa\u0142 Skarbek-Malczewski}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish painter and mountaineer}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Rafa\u0142 Malczewski\n| image        = Jacek Malczewski - Portret syna Rafa\u0142a.jpg\n| image_size   = 250 px\n| caption      = [[Jacek Malczewski]]  Portrait of his son, Rafa\u0142\n| birth_date    = 24 October 1892\n| birth_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1965|02|15|1892|10|24|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Montreal]], [[Canada]]\n}}\n'''Rafa\u0142 Marceli Ludwik Fortunat J\u00f3zef Malczewski''' (24 October 1892 - 15 February 1965) was a Polish landscape and portrait painter, draughtsman, author and columnist. He was a noted [[Tatra Mountains|Tatra mountaineer]], [[Skiing in the Snow|skier]] and populariser of the [[Tatra Mountains]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his Tatra-themed painting |author=Lenartowicz, \u015awiatos\u0142aw|url=http://muzea.malopolska.pl/en/czy-wiesz-ze/-/a/o-rafale-malczewskim-i-jego-malarstwie-tatrzanskim?view=full|publisher=muzea.malopolska.pl|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Rafa\u0142 Malczewski - Kazimierz Sichulski.jpg|thumb|1923 Cartoon of Malczewski by [[Kazimierz Sichulski]]]]\n[[File:Zamar\u0142a Turnia.jpg|thumb|left|South face of ''Zamar\u0142a Turnia'' in the [[Tatra Mountains]]]]\nHe was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], four years after his sister, Julia, the son of Maria, n\u0117e Gralewska, and her husband the celebrated [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]] painter and professor of Fine Art, [[Jacek Malczewski]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416120803/http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-visual-arts-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/jacek-malczewski | url-status=dead | archive-date=2013-04-16 | title=Jacek Malczewski | publisher=Instytut Sztuki Polskiej Akademii Nauk. Culture.pl | work=Symbolizm w polskim malarstwie prze\u0142omu XIX i XX wieku | date=October 2002 | accessdate=October 17, 2012 | author=Kossowska, Irena | language=Polish}}</ref><ref name = \"IK\">{{cite web|author= Kossowska, Irena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski|date=2001|url= https://culture.pl/en/artist/rafal-malczewski|publisher=culture.pl|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> He graduated from the Saint Jacek High School in the city. From 1910\u20131915 he studied at the [[University of Vienna]]. He took courses philosophy, architecture and [[agronomy]]. On his return to Krak\u00f3w he entered the [[Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts]], and also worked in his father's studio. In 1915 he began to travel frequently to [[Zakopane]] where he spent extensive periods, to climb, ski and paint, until the [[outbreak of World War II]]. He joined the local [[Mountain rescue]] team, [[Tatrza\u0144skie Ochotnicze Pogotowie Ratunkowe|TOPR]]. However in 1917 on the south face of \"Zamar\u0142a Turnia\" he and his climbing companion, Stanis\u0142aw Bronikowski, were caught in a climbing accident in which his friend died, while Malczewski clung to a hook all night awaiting rescue.\n\nIn October 1917 he married Bronis\u0142awa Dziadosz, an English teacher four years his senior and a [[US citizen]] of Polish descent who had immigrated into Poland. In November of the same year, their son Krzysztof was born. Despite an unhappy partnership, the couple went on to have a second child, Zofia. Their poor financial situation led to Rafa\u0142's artist father helping them out. In 1923 he bought for them a chalet called \"Marysin\".\n\nRafa\u0142 Malczewski was an associate and friend of a group of artists, musicians and intellectuals who would congregate in the [[Mountain resort]] of Zakopane in the early part of the 20th century. They included [[Stanis\u0142aw Ignacy Witkiewicz]], [[Karol Szymanowski]], [[Kornel Makuszy\u0144ski]], [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]. In 1932 he joined the \"Rhythm Association of artists (Stowarzyszenie Artyst\u00f3w Polskich \u201eRytm\u201d) and was a set designer for productions of [[Strindberg]] and [[Stanis\u0142aw Witkiewicz]] at the ''Formistyczny Theatre'' in Zakopane. In 1937 he was awarded the \"Wawrzyn Akademicki\" award from the [[Polska Akademia Literatury]] \"for services to Polish art\".<ref>Rocznik Polskiej Akademii Literatury 1937\u20131938, Warsaw 1939, p. 175.</ref> 1938 he donated part of his artistic output to the newly re-opened [[National Museum of Warsaw]] to which, several years earlier on account of his material difficulties, he had sold the entirety of his father's work left to him by Malczewski Sr.\n\n== Travels ==\n[[File:Rafal Malczewski Ottawa.jpg|thumb|Rafa\u0142 Malczewski in [[Ottawa]]. He settled in [[Canada]] in 1942]]\nIn 1939 after the [[outbreak of World War II]], having already abandoned his wife and children, he escaped over the [[Slovakia|Slovak]] border, with his partner Zofia Mikucka, and via [[Budapest]] and [[Venice]] made his way to [[Paris]]. There he fell on the generosity of the Polish embassy there to help him out of another financial difficulty. In 1940 they travelled on to [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]], where they stayed for four months. At the beginning of 1941 they moved to [[Brazil]]. At first they stayed in [[Rio de Janeiro]] where he was able to sell some of his paintings which consisted of water colour landscapes of Rio, [[Curitiba]] and of [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Parana]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=CANADIAN ART CRITICS ON RAFA\u0141 MALCZEWSKI|author= Krzy\u017canowski, Jerzy R.|journal=The Polish Review|volume= 38, No. 2 |date=1993|pages=191-201}}</ref><ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\nIn 1942 they moved to Curitiba to stay with his cousin, Maria Bochdan-Niedenthal. Shortly after, he succeeded in obtaining Canadian visas for himself and his girlfriend, Zofia, for travel to [[Ottawa]]. By December 1942 he held his first Canadian exhibition in the [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]. He managed to persuade the [[Canadian railways]] to sponsor him and Zofia to travel across [[Canada]] and the [[USA]] in search of artistic subjects. He spent the winter of 1943 in the [[Rocky Mountains]], which led to a series of canvases that kept him supplied for many exhibitions until 1949. A stay in [[New York City|New York]] in 1950 was fruitful enough for further sales of his work. \n\nDespite developing problems with his sight, like his father before him, the ensuing years saw a great flowering of his painting and writing. After his wife, Bronislawa died in Warsaw in 1953, he finally married Zofia Mikucka.<ref>{{cite book|title=Coraz trudniej \u017cy\u0107, a umrze\u0107 strach, Listy 1952\u20131955|trans-title=It gets more difficult to live, but perish the thought of dying. Letters 1952-1955 |authors =  Zofia and Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and [[Jan Lecho\u0144|Lecho\u0144, Jan]]|publisher=Biblioteka Wi\u0119zi|lang=pl|isbn=978-8-3603-5649-4}}\n</ref> A stroke in 1957 led to a partial paralysis which obliged him to give up painting in oils, but he was able to continue with water colours. He managed to obtain sponsorship from the CIA-controlled [[Radio Free Europe]] and from [[Quebec City]]. In 1959 the daughter of Zofia Malczewska-Kondracka invited him to visit Poland. Despite great nostalgia for the south of the country, he  resolved to remain in Canada, but his journey was described in his memoir, ''Wspomnieniach z Polski'' and serialised in the [[London]] \u00e9migr\u00e9 paper,[[Wiadomo\u015bci (London magazine)|Wiadomo\u015bci]]. From 1961 he was kept by his daughter, Zofia, and three years later, in 1964 his last exhibition took place in [[Montreal]]. He died and was buried there in 1965.<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\n== Characteristics of his art ==\nMagdalena Ma\u0142etko has emphasised several pointers to understand Malczewski's art. His successful artist father wished him to have a more reliable career than his own. While at the University of Vienna Malczewski studied [[Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]] as part of the philosophy course, but he failed to complete his degree. He never got over the death of his close friend and climbing partner Bronikowski, who died on a climb they did together in 1917. His first marriage was an attempt to get over his grief and was loveless, and more of a duty due to Bronis\u0142awa's pregnancy. Painting came to him instinctually as he watched his prolific father working in his studio. Malczewski was an artist difficult to categorise, although he developed his own distinctive style. This has been called \"hyper realism\" (Witkacy) and \"naive\". His themes were predominantly empty vistas, mountain scenery, snowscapes and glassy lakes. He also did portraits, cartoons and a series of rally cars and industrial scenery in [[Silesia]]. The great hiatus of his life was leaving his family and his beloved Zakopane in 1939. Three years later he had settled in Canada having travelled through Southern Europe and Brazil, where his palette responded to the colour and light. His later life was a struggle with increasing blindness and paralysis which allowed him only to use water colour, alongside his writing, which he managed to do until his death.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ma\u0142etko, Magdalena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i jego widzenie nowoczesno\u015bci|date=2009   |url=https://www.kul.pl/files/564/public/ARTykuly/ARTykuly002/ARTykuly_nr002_2009_MM_s22.pdf|lang=pl|publisher=www.kul.pl|access-date=2020-04-14|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his vision of modernity}}</ref>\n\n== Selected exhibitions and awards==\nMalczewski's first public show was with [[Witkacy]] at Garlinski's Salon in Warsaw in 1924.<ref name = \"IK\"/> Solo shows followed in:\n* Zakopane (1926)\n* Warsaw (1928, 1929, 1935, 1938)\n* Krak\u00f3w (1930, 1932) \n* [[Lodz|\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] (1935)\n* [[Katowice]] (1938) \n* Montreal Museum of Arts ( 1942)\n* Dominion Gallery (1949)  \n* Corcoran Gallery, [[Washington, D.C.]] (1944).<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\nAs a member of the Society for the Propagation of Polish Art Abroad, he participated in the following group exhibitions:\n* [[Prague]] and [[Helsinki]] (1929)\n* Vienna and Paris (1928) \n* [[Brussels]] and [[The Hague]] (1929)\n* Budapest and [[Copenhagen]] (1930)\n* Venice (13th Biennale) and [[Los Angeles]] (1932)\n* [[Moscow]], [[Edinburgh]], and [[San Francisco]] (1933)\n* New York (1933)\n* [[Berlin]] (1936)\n* [[Pittsburgh]] (1938)\n* [[Ottawa]] (1942)\n* [[Detroit]] (1945) \n* [[Montreal]] (1954). \nAmong the many awards he received were:\n* President [[Ignacy Mo\u015bcicki]] prize 1930\n* Golden laurel of ''Polska Akademia Literatury'' 1937\n* Gold Medal for his ''Wiosna w g\u00f3rach'' [\"Spring in the mountains\"] at the Paris [[Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne]] 1937\n* ''The Visual Arts Prize'' of Paris-based Polish-language monthly, ''[[Kultura]]'' 1962.<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n\n== Selected written work ==\nIn his writing Rafa\u0142 Malczewski evoked the atmosphere of [[Interbellum Poland|interbellum]] Zakopane:\n* ''Od cepra do wariata'', [From Lowland Dweller to Madman]\n* ''Narkotyk g\u00f3r. Nowele tatrza\u0144skie'', [\"Addicted to mountains. Tatran novellas\"] (1928)\n* ''Tatry i Podhale'' [\"The Tatras and their Foothills\"] (1935)\n* ''G\u00f3ry wo\u0142aj\u0105'' [\"The Mountains Beckon\"] (1939).<ref name = \"IK\"/>\n* ''P\u0119pek \u015bwiata. Wspomnienia z Zakopanego'', [\"The Navel of the World. Memories of Zakopane\"].<ref>{{cite book|author=Malczewski, Rafa\u0142|title=P\u0119pek \u015bwiata. Wspomnienia z Zakopanego|date=1960|publisher= Wydawnictwo LTW|url=http://www.lubimyczytac.pl/ksiazka/87425/pepek-swiata-wspomnienia-z-zakopanego|lang=pl}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Folga-Januszewska, Dorota|title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i Mit Zakopanego|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and the Myth of Zakopane|lang=pl|publisher=Bosz|date=2006|volume=1|isbn=978-8-3897-4734-1}}\n* {{cite book|author=Folga-Januszewska, Dorota|title=Zakopane w czasach Rafa\u0142a Malczewskiego|editor=Jab\u0142o\u0144ska, Teresa|trans-title=Zakopane in the Times of Rafa\u0142 Malczewski|lang=pl|publisher=Bosz|date=2006|volume=2|isbn=978-8-3897-4734-1}}\n* {{cite web|author=Ma\u0142etko, Magdalena|title= Rafa\u0142 Malczewski i jego widzenie nowoczesno\u015bci|date=2009   |url=https://www.kul.pl/files/564/public/ARTykuly/ARTykuly002/ARTykuly_nr002_2009_MM_s22.pdf|lang=pl|publisher=www.kul.pl Art History Students magazine, [[Catholic University of Lublin]]|access-date=2020-04-14|trans-title=Rafa\u0142 Malczewski and his vision of modernity}}\n* {{cite web|author=Szymalak-Bugajska, Paulina|date=2017|url=https://niezlasztuka.net/o-sztuce/jacek-malczewski-rycerz-polskiej-sztuki/|title=Jacek Malczewski \u2013 rycerz polskiej sztuki|trans-title=Jacek Malczewski - Knight of Polish Art|lang=pl|publisher=niezlasztuka.net|access-date=2020-04-14}} Contains illustrations and quotes from Malczewski family, including Rafa\u0142.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pinakoteka.zascianek.pl/Malczewski_R/Index.htm Paintings by Rafa\u0142 Malczewski]\n* [https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/aac-aic/artiste_detailler_bas-artist_detail_bas.app?rID=10818&fID=2&lang=en&qlang=en&pID=672&ps=50&sort=AM_ASC& Artists in Canada - Canadian Government entry]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malczewski, Rafa\u0142}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Polish painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish painters]]\n[[Category:Polish landscape painters]]\n[[Category:Jan Matejko Academy of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Zakopane]]\n[[Category:Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:People from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Polish mountain climbers]]\n", "name_user": "Po Mieczu", "label": "safe", "comment": "copyedits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafa%C5%82_Malczewski"}
{"title_page": "Richard Franklin (director)", "text_new": "{{confused|Richard Franklin (actor)}}{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person    \n| name          =  Richard Franklin\n| image         =  Richard Franklin (director).jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|7|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2007|7|11|1948|7|15}}\n| death_place   = Melbourne, Victoria, Australia\n| occupation    = [[Film director]]\n| birthname     =  \n| spouse        = \n| years_active  = 1975\u20132003\n}}\n\n'''Richard Franklin''' (15 July 1948 \u2013 11 July 2007) was an [[Australia]]n  [[film director]].<ref name=\"atdd\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,22065571-16947,00.html |work=[[The Australian]] |first=Sandy |last=George |title=Australian thriller director dies |date=2007-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nFranklin was born and grew up in [[Brighton, Victoria|Brighton]], [[Melbourne]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/people/a-passionate-witty-precise-filmmaker/2007/07/19/1184559953321.html |first=Brian |last=McFarlane |title=A passionate, witty, precise filmmaker |format=obituary |work=[[The Age]] |date=2007-07-20}}</ref> the son of Margaret Anne (Jacobson) and Rea Richard Franklin, an engineering company director.<ref>http://www.filmreference.com/film/76/Richard-Franklin.html</ref> He was educated at [[Haileybury, Melbourne|Haileybury College]]. In the 1960s, Franklin was the drummer in the Melbourne band [[The Pink Finks]], which also featured [[Ross Wilson (musician)|Ross Wilson]] and [[Ross Hannaford]], later of [[Daddy Cool (band)|Daddy Cool]]. The band released several singles, none of which had any significant chart success.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milesago.com/Artists/pinkfinks.htm |title=The Pink Finks |work=MILESAGO: Australasian Music and Popular Culture 1964-1975}}</ref> Franklin decided upon a career in film rather than music. He went on to study film at [[The University of Southern California]] alongside other notable directors [[George Lucas]], [[Robert Zemeckis]] and [[John Carpenter]]. Franklin was a devotee of [[Alfred Hitchcock]] (ever since he saw ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' at the age of 12), and his attempt to arrange for a screening of Hitchcock's ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) at USC resulted in a phone-call from Hitchcock himself. Franklin invited Hitchcock to give a lecture at the university, and subsequently he became good friends with the director.<ref name=\"atdd\" />\n\n==Directing career==\n\nFranklin returned to Australia in the 1970s, when the country's film industry was experiencing a resurgence. He directed four episodes of the Australian police drama ''[[Homicide (Australian TV series)|Homicide]]'' before directing the bawdy 1975 sex comedy feature ''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]'' and the 1976 soft-core pornography feature ''[[Fantasm]]''. Franklin's next film was the cult horror movie ''[[Patrick (1978 film)|Patrick]]'' (1978), written by [[Everett De Roche]], about a man in a coma who uses telekinesis to create murder and mayhem in a hospital. Franklin gave De Roche a copy of the screenplay of Alfred Hitchcock's ''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954), and De Roche suggested a movie with the plot of ''Rear Window'' taking place in a moving vehicle. The result was ''[[Roadgames]]'' (1981), directed by Franklin from a screenplay by De Roche. Filmed and set in Australia, and starring American actors [[Stacy Keach]] and [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] (the latter of whom Franklin met whilst visiting his one-time USC classmate John Carpenter on the set of ''[[The Fog]]''), ''Roadgames'' was the most expensive Australian movie ever made at the time of its release in 1981.<ref name=\"atdd\" />\n\n===US films===\nAfter moving to Hollywood, Richard Franklin directed ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'' (1983), the first sequel to Hitchcock's 1960 classic ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', with [[Anthony Perkins]] reprising the role of [[Norman Bates]]. The film was a financial success and received generally good reviews (it also led to a further two sequels, neither of which Franklin was involved with). Franklin then directed the 1984 spy/adventure movie ''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'', starring [[Henry Thomas]] and [[Dabney Coleman]]. The film was a remake of ''[[The Window (1949 film)|The Window]]'' (1949), which was in turn based on the short story \"The Boy Who Cried Murder\" by [[Cornell Woolrich]] (Woolrich's short story \"It Had to Be Murder\" was adapted into Hitchcock's ''Rear Window'', which was the inspiration for Franklin's ''Road Games''). \n\nFranklin was going to make ''The Lost Boys'' at one stage<ref>http://www.avclub.com/article/tom-holland-his-seminal-vampire-flick-fright-night-223200</ref> but his next film was ''[[Link (film)|Link]]'' (1986) a British horror movie (starring [[Elisabeth Shue]] and [[Terence Stamp]]) about a super-intelligent, murderous [[orangutan]]. The film reunited Franklin with screenwriter Everett De Roche. \n\nFranklin was disillusioned with Hollywood after the experience of directing the 1991 action/thriller ''[[F/X2|FX2: The Deadly Art Of Illusion]]'' (starring [[Bryan Brown]] and [[Brian Dennehy]]).\n\n===Return to Australia===\nHe returned to Australia where he filmed ''[[Hotel Sorrento]]'' (1995) and ''[[Brilliant Lies]]'' (1996). Franklin called these films\n<blockquote>Very conscious attempts to prove that I could do what Australian filmmakers like Peter Weir and Bruce Beresford had done, which was make very classy arthouse types of films. Peter Weir was being offered material like ''Witness'', that I would have loved to have directed, because he was perceived as an arthouse filmmaker. Whereas even in Hollywood I was perceived as a genre filmmaker, and not able to get these special elements that would win Oscars and the like.<ref name=\"trash\">[http://mondostumpo.blogspot.com.au/2007/11/richard-franklin-interview-2002.html Interview with Richard Franklin, ''Mondo Stump'',  originally published in Eros Magazine Vol 3 No 1 (2003), Canberra] accessed 15 October 2012</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Final years===\nFranklin's most recent film, ''[[Visitors (2003 film)|Visitors]]'', was shot in 2003.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Richard Franklin: Visitors |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/deepend/stories/2003/997656.htm |series=The Deep End |credits=Julie Rigg |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |airdate=2003-11-26}}</ref> He lectured at Swinburne School of Film and Television in Australia until his death.\n\nRichard Franklin died of [[prostate cancer]] on 11 July 2007, four days before his 59th birthday.<ref name=\"atdd\" /> The documentary film ''[[Not Quite Hollywood|Not Quite Hollywood: The Wild, Untold Story of Ozploitation!]]'' (2008), for which Franklin was interviewed, was released after his death and was dedicated to him. Before his death, Franklin was set to be interviewed for ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'', a documentary that examined the [[Psycho (film series)|Psycho]] franchise; however, the said interview with him was never filmed. Nevertheless, Franklin was enthusiastic about the documentary project and had wanted to do whatever he could to assist in its production.\n\n[[Quentin Tarantino]] has cited ''Roadgames'' as his favourite Australian movie,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcorntaxi.com.au/event.php?event_id=273 |title=Event |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726092619/http://www.popcorntaxi.com.au/event.php?event_id=273 |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> and he screened ''Psycho II'' at the sixth [[Quentin Tarantino Film Festival]] (2005).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dumbdistraction.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=73 |title=QT6 - Quentin Tarantino Film Festival VI: Day 2 |work=web.archive.org |date=3 April 2007 |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024223127/http://dumbdistraction.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=73 |archivedate=24 October 2007 }}</ref> Tarantino revealed in an interview that when he was a teenager, he wanted to write a book on genre filmmakers, and Richard Franklin was one of the directors he wanted to engage in conversation for it.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peary |first=Gerald |authorlink=Gerald Peary |title=A Brief Talk with Quentin Tarantino |url=http://www.geraldpeary.com/books/tarantino_interview.html |date=August 1992}} Transcript of an interview with Tarantino at the 1992 Montreal World Film Festival.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Producer\n! Writer\n! Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|Also known as ''Dick Down Under''\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Fantasm]]''\n|{{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|Credited as \"Richard Bruce\"\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Patrick (1978 film)|Patrick]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Film]]\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Roadgames]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Link (film)|Link]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[F/X2]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Running Delilah]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|[[Television film]]\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Hotel Sorrento]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Film]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]] - Grand Prix\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Brilliant Lies]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[One Way Ticket (1997 film)|One Way Ticket]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|TV film\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The Lost World (TV series)|The Lost World]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|Pilot film (episodes 1 & 2) + four additional episodes\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Visitors (2003 film)|Visitors]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Not Quite Hollywood: The Wild, Untold Story of Ozploitation!]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|Self\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Graham |first=Aaron W. |title=Richard Franklin |work=Senses of Cinema |issue=36 |date=July 2005 |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/franklin/}} An article surveying Franklin's filmmaking career.\n*{{cite web |title=Senses of Cinema - Richard Franklin |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/author/richard-franklin/}} Franklin wrote three articles for ''[[Senses of Cinema]]'' that are accessible from this webpage.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0002207|name=Richard Franklin}}\n\n{{Richard Franklin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franklin, Richard}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Male drummers]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Deaths from prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury, Melbourne]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century drummers]]\n[[Category:Horror film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{confused|Richard Franklin (actor)}}{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person    \n| name          =  Richard Franklin\n| image         =  Richard Franklin (director).jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|7|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2007|7|11|1948|7|15}}\n| death_place   = Melbourne, Victoria, Australia\n| occupation    = [[Film director]]\n| birthname     =  \n| spouse        = \n| years_active  = 1975\u20132003\n}}\n\n'''Richard Franklin''' (15 July 1948 \u2013 11 July 2007) was an [[Australia]]n  [[film director]].<ref name=\"atdd\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,22065571-16947,00.html |work=[[The Australian]] |first=Sandy |last=George |title=Australian thriller director dies |date=2007-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nFranklin was born and grew up in [[Brighton, Victoria|Brighton]], [[Melbourne]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/people/a-passionate-witty-precise-filmmaker/2007/07/19/1184559953321.html |first=Brian |last=McFarlane |title=A passionate, witty, precise filmmaker |format=obituary |work=[[The Age]] |date=2007-07-20}}</ref> the son of Margaret Anne (Jacobson) and Rea Richard Franklin, an engineering company director.<ref>http://www.filmreference.com/film/76/Richard-Franklin.html</ref> He was educated at [[Haileybury, Melbourne|Haileybury College]]. In the 1960s, Franklin was the drummer in the Melbourne band [[The Pink Finks]], which also featured [[Ross Wilson (musician)|Ross Wilson]] and [[Ross Hannaford]], later of [[Daddy Cool (band)|Daddy Cool]]. The band released several singles, none of which had any significant chart success.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milesago.com/Artists/pinkfinks.htm |title=The Pink Finks |work=MILESAGO: Australasian Music and Popular Culture 1964-1975}}</ref> Franklin decided upon a career in film rather than music. He went on to study film at [[The University of Southern California]] alongside other notable directors [[George Lucas]], [[Robert Zemeckis]] and [[John Carpenter]]. Franklin was a devotee of [[Alfred Hitchcock]] (ever since he saw ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' at the age of 12), and his attempt to arrange for a screening of Hitchcock's ''[[Rope (film)|Rope]]'' (1948) at USC resulted in a phone-call from Hitchcock himself. Franklin invited Hitchcock to give a lecture at the university, and subsequently he became good friends with the director.<ref name=\"atdd\" />\n\n==Directing career==\n\nFranklin returned to Australia in the 1970s, when the country's film industry was experiencing a resurgence. He directed four episodes of the Australian police drama ''[[Homicide (Australian TV series)|Homicide]]'' before directing the bawdy 1975 sex comedy feature ''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]'' and the 1976 soft-core pornography feature ''[[Fantasm]]''. Franklin's next film was the cult horror movie ''[[Patrick (1978 film)|Patrick]]'' (1978), written by [[Everett De Roche]], about a man in a coma who uses telekinesis to create murder and mayhem in a hospital. Franklin gave De Roche a copy of the screenplay of Alfred Hitchcock's ''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954), and De Roche suggested a movie with the plot of ''Rear Window'' taking place in a moving vehicle. The result was ''[[Roadgames]]'' (1981), directed by Franklin from a screenplay by De Roche. Filmed and set in Australia, and starring American actors [[Stacy Keach]] and [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] (the latter of whom Franklin met whilst visiting his one-time USC classmate John Carpenter on the set of ''[[The Fog]]''), ''Roadgames'' was the most expensive Australian movie ever made at the time of its release in 1981.<ref name=\"atdd\" />\n\n===US films===\nAfter moving to Hollywood, Richard Franklin directed ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'' (1983), the first sequel to Hitchcock's 1960 classic ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', with [[Anthony Perkins]] reprising the role of [[Norman Bates]]. The film was a financial success and received generally good reviews (it also led to a further two sequels, neither of which Franklin was involved with). Franklin then directed the 1984 spy/adventure movie ''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'', starring [[Henry Thomas]] and [[Dabney Coleman]]. The film was a remake of ''[[The Window (1949 film)|The Window]]'' (1949), which was in turn based on the short story \"The Boy Who Cried Murder\" by [[Cornell Woolrich]] (Woolrich's short story \"It Had to Be Murder\" was adapted into Hitchcock's ''Rear Window'', which was the inspiration for Franklin's ''Road Games''). \n\nFranklin was going to make ''The Lost Boys'' at one stage<ref>http://www.avclub.com/article/tom-holland-his-seminal-vampire-flick-fright-night-223200</ref> but his next film was ''[[Link (film)|Link]]'' (1986) a British horror movie (starring [[Elisabeth Shue]] and [[Terence Stamp]]) about a super-intelligent, murderous [[orangutan]]. The film reunited Franklin with screenwriter Everett De Roche. \n\nFranklin was disillusioned with Hollywood after the experience of directing the 1991 action/thriller ''[[F/X2|FX2: The Deadly Art Of Illusion]]'' (starring [[Bryan Brown]] and [[Brian Dennehy]]).\n\n===Return to Australia===\nHe returned to Australia where he filmed ''[[Hotel Sorrento]]'' (1995) and ''[[Brilliant Lies]]'' (1996). Franklin called these films\n<blockquote>Very conscious attempts to prove that I could do what Australian filmmakers like Peter Weir and Bruce Beresford had done, which was make very classy arthouse types of films. Peter Weir was being offered material like ''Witness'', that I would have loved to have directed, because he was perceived as an arthouse filmmaker. Whereas even in Hollywood I was perceived as a genre filmmaker, and not able to get these special elements that would win Oscars and the like.<ref name=\"trash\">[http://mondostumpo.blogspot.com.au/2007/11/richard-franklin-interview-2002.html Interview with Richard Franklin, ''Mondo Stump'',  originally published in Eros Magazine Vol 3 No 1 (2003), Canberra] accessed 15 October 2012</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Final years===\nFranklin's most recent film, ''[[Visitors (2003 film)|Visitors]]'', was shot in 2003.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Richard Franklin: Visitors |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/deepend/stories/2003/997656.htm |series=The Deep End |credits=Julie Rigg |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |airdate=2003-11-26}}</ref> He lectured at Swinburne School of Film and Television in Australia until his death.\n\nRichard Franklin died of [[prostate cancer]] on 11 July 2007, four days before his 59th birthday.<ref name=\"atdd\" /> The documentary film ''[[Not Quite Hollywood|Not Quite Hollywood: The Wild, Untold Story of Ozploitation!]]'' (2008), for which Franklin was interviewed, was released after his death and was dedicated to him. Before his death, Franklin was set to be interviewed for ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'', a documentary that examined the [[Psycho (film series)|Psycho]] franchise; however, the said interview with him was never filmed. Nevertheless, Franklin was enthusiastic about the documentary project and had wanted to do whatever he could to assist in its production.\n\n[[Quentin Tarantino]] has cited ''Roadgames'' as his favourite Australian movie,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcorntaxi.com.au/event.php?event_id=273 |title=Event |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726092619/http://www.popcorntaxi.com.au/event.php?event_id=273 |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> and he screened ''Psycho II'' at the sixth [[Quentin Tarantino Film Festival]] (2005).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dumbdistraction.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=73 |title=QT6 - Quentin Tarantino Film Festival VI: Day 2 |work=web.archive.org |date=3 April 2007 |accessdate=9 April 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024223127/http://dumbdistraction.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=73 |archivedate=24 October 2007 }}</ref> Tarantino revealed in an interview that when he was a teenager, he wanted to write a book on genre filmmakers, and Richard Franklin was one of the directors he wanted to engage in conversation for it.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peary |first=Gerald |authorlink=Gerald Peary |title=A Brief Talk with Quentin Tarantino |url=http://www.geraldpeary.com/books/tarantino_interview.html |date=August 1992}} Transcript of an interview with Tarantino at the 1992 Montreal World Film Festival.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Producer\n! Writer\n! Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[The True Story of Eskimo Nell]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|Also known as ''Dick Down Under''\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Fantasm]]''\n|{{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Patrick (1978 film)|Patrick]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Film]]\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Roadgames]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Link (film)|Link]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[F/X2]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Running Delilah]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|[[Television film]]\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Hotel Sorrento]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Film]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[AACTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[Tokyo International Film Festival]] - Grand Prix\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Brilliant Lies]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[One Way Ticket (1997 film)|One Way Ticket]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|TV film\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The Lost World (TV series)|The Lost World]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|Pilot film (episodes 1 & 2) + four additional episodes\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Visitors (2003 film)|Visitors]]''\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Not Quite Hollywood: The Wild, Untold Story of Ozploitation!]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|Self\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Graham |first=Aaron W. |title=Richard Franklin |work=Senses of Cinema |issue=36 |date=July 2005 |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/franklin/}} An article surveying Franklin's filmmaking career.\n*{{cite web |title=Senses of Cinema - Richard Franklin |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/author/richard-franklin/}} Franklin wrote three articles for ''[[Senses of Cinema]]'' that are accessible from this webpage.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0002207|name=Richard Franklin}}\n\n{{Richard Franklin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franklin, Richard}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Male drummers]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Deaths from prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury, Melbourne]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century drummers]]\n[[Category:Horror film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Franklin_(director)"}
{"title_page": "Chandrika Roy", "text_new": "\u2192{{Short description|politician from Bihar, India}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| native_name         = {{lang|hi|\u091a\u0928\u094d\u0926\u094d\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0930\u093e\u092f}}\n| office              = Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start          = {{Start date|df=y|2015|11}}\n| constituency        = [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Parsa]]\n| predecessor         = Chhotelal Rai\n| office2             = Minister of Transport Department, Bihar\n| term_start2         = {{Start date|df=y|2015|11|20}}\n| term_end2           = {{Start date|df=y|2017|7|26}}\n| predecessor2        = [[Brishin Patel]]\n| successor2          = [[Santosh Kumar Nirala]]\n| office3             = Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = {{Start date|df=y|1985}}\n| term_end3           = {{Start date|df=y|2005}}\n| constituency3       = [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Parsa]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1957|12|31}}\n| birth_place         = Bajahiya, [[Saran district]], [[Bihar]]\n| spouse              = Purnima Roy\n| children            = 3\n| father              = [[Daroga Prasad Rai]]\n| education           = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Master of Arts|M.A.]]\n*[[PhD]]}}\n}}\n'''Chandrika Roy''' is an Indian politician from [[Saran district]] of [[Bihar]], [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/chandrika-roy/candidates/candidateid-11340.cms|title=Chandrika Roy: Chandrika Roy RJD from SARAN in Lok Sabha Elections {{!}} Chandrika Roy News, images and videos|last=|first=|date=|website=The Economic Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404193026/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/chandrika-roy/candidates/candidateid-11340.cms|archive-date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He is a Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] representing [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]].\n\n== Political career ==\nRoy made entry into politics in 1985 as member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]. Again in [[1990 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|1990]], [[1995 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|1995]] and [[2000 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2000]], he won from the same constituency. In [[October 2005 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|October 2005]] and [[2010 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2010]] Bihar Legislative Assembly elections, he lost to Chhotelal Rai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latestly.com/elections/assembly-elections/bihar/2010/parsa/|title=\ud83d\uddf3\ufe0f Chhotelal Rai winner in Parsa, Bihar Assembly Elections 2010: LIVE Results & Latest News: Election Dates, Polling Schedule, Election Results & Live Election Updates|last=|first=|date=|website=LatestLY|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404194007/https://www.latestly.com/elections/assembly-elections/bihar/2010/parsa/|archive-date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He also held the position as Minister of Transport Department of [[Government of Bihar]] from 2015 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/5812015.pdf|title=\u092e\u0941\u0916\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u090f\u0902\u0935 \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u094b \u0938\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093e\u0917\u094b \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f \u0915\u093e \u0906\u0935\u0902\u091f\u0928|last=|first=|date=2015-11-20|website=Cabinet Secretariat Dept.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407183903/http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/5812015.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/M2032017.pdf|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u0925\u093e \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092a\u0930\u093f\u0937\u0926 \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u0926\u0938\u094d\u092f \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0930\u0939\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092c\u0928\u094d\u0927 \u092e\u0947\u0902\u0964|last=|first=|date=2017-07-27|website=Cabinet Secretariat Dept.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407184422/http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/M2032017.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Currently, he is serving as Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] since [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2015]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/pdf/member_profile/121.pdf|title=Know your MLA|last=|first=|date=|website=Bihar Vidhan Sabha|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404193201/http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/pdf/member_profile/121.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-05|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHe quit the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] due to the marital dispute between his daughter and RJD president [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]'s son [[Tej Pratap Yadav]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/chandrika-roy-tej-pratap-yadavs-father-in-law-quits-rashtriya-janata-dal-2180362|title=Chandrika Rai, Tej Pratap's Father-In-Law, Quits Rashtriya Janata Dal|last=|first=|date=|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162600/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/chandrika-rai-tej-pratap-yadavs-father-in-law-quits-rashtriya-janata-dal-2180362|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/opinion/it-is-a-clash-of-stylish-titans-in-bihars-saran-as-rajiv-rudy-chandrika-rai-give-classy-twist-to-ls-battle-2126485.html|title=It is a Clash of \u2018Stylish\u2019 Titans in Bihar\u2019s Saran as Rajiv Rudy, Chandrika Rai Give Classy Twist to LS Battle|last=|first=|date=2019-05-03|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162749/https://www.news18.com/news/opinion/it-is-a-clash-of-stylish-titans-in-bihars-saran-as-rajiv-rudy-chandrika-rai-give-classy-twist-to-ls-battle-2126485.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life==\n\nChandrika Roy is the second son of the five sons of [[Daroga Prasad Rai]]. Chandrika Rai's daughter Aishwarya Roy married to [[Tej Pratap Yadav]], the eldest son of [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]] on 12 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/aishwarya-rai-granddaughter-of-ex-bihar-cm-daroga-rai-to-marry-lalu-prasads-son-tej-pratap-yadav-5125826/|title=Aishwarya Rai, granddaughter of former Bihar CM Daroga Rai, to marry Lalu Prasad\u2019s son Tej Pratap Yadav|last=|first=|date=2018-04-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162943/https://indianexpress.com/article/india/aishwarya-rai-granddaughter-of-ex-bihar-cm-daroga-rai-to-marry-lalu-prasads-son-tej-pratap-yadav-5125826/|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Tributes-paid-to-Daroga-Prasad-Rai/articleshow/194090705.cms|title=Tributes paid to Daroga Prasad Roy {{!}} Patna News - Times of India|last=Sep 3|first=|last2=2001|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407163121/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Tributes-paid-to-Daroga-Prasad-Rai/articleshow/194090705.cms?referral=PM|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Ist|first3=00:41}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rai, Chandrika}}\n[[Category:Members of the Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 1985\u20131990]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 1990\u20131995]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 1995\u20132000]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2000\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2015\u2013]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Janata Dal politicians]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|politician from Bihar, India}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| native_name         = {{lang|hi|\u091a\u0928\u094d\u0926\u094d\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0930\u093e\u092f}}\n| office              = Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start          = {{Start date|df=y|2015|11}}\n| constituency        = [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Parsa]]\n| predecessor         = Chhotelal Rai\n| office2             = Minister of Transport Department, Bihar\n| term_start2         = {{Start date|df=y|2015|11|20}}\n| term_end2           = {{Start date|df=y|2017|7|26}}\n| predecessor2        = [[Brishin Patel]]\n| successor2          = [[Santosh Kumar Nirala]]\n| office3             = Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = {{Start date|df=y|1985}}\n| term_end3           = {{Start date|df=y|2005}}\n| constituency3       = [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Parsa]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1957|12|31}}\n| birth_place         = Bajahiya, [[Saran district]], [[Bihar]]\n| spouse              = Purnima Roy\n| children            = 3\n| father              = [[Daroga Prasad Rai]]\n| education           = {{Flatlist|\n*[[Master of Arts|M.A.]]\n*[[PhD]]}}\n}}\n'''Chandrika Roy''' is an Indian politician from [[Saran district]] of [[Bihar]], [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/chandrika-roy/candidates/candidateid-11340.cms|title=Chandrika Roy: Chandrika Roy RJD from SARAN in Lok Sabha Elections {{!}} Chandrika Roy News, images and videos|last=|first=|date=|website=The Economic Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404193026/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/chandrika-roy/candidates/candidateid-11340.cms|archive-date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He is a Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] representing [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]].\n\n== Political career ==\nRoy made entry into politics in 1985 as member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]. Again in [[1990 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|1990]], [[1995 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|1995]] and [[2000 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2000]], he won from the same constituency. In [[October 2005 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|October 2005]] and [[2010 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2010]] Bihar Legislative Assembly elections, he lost to Chhotelal Rai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latestly.com/elections/assembly-elections/bihar/2010/parsa/|title=\ud83d\uddf3\ufe0f Chhotelal Rai winner in Parsa, Bihar Assembly Elections 2010: LIVE Results & Latest News: Election Dates, Polling Schedule, Election Results & Live Election Updates|last=|first=|date=|website=LatestLY|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404194007/https://www.latestly.com/elections/assembly-elections/bihar/2010/parsa/|archive-date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> He also held the position as Minister of Transport Department of [[Government of Bihar]] from 2015 to 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/5812015.pdf|title=\u092e\u0941\u0916\u094d\u092f\u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u090f\u0902\u0935 \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u094b \u0938\u0930\u0915\u093e\u0930 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u093e\u0917\u094b \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f \u0915\u093e \u0906\u0935\u0902\u091f\u0928|last=|first=|date=2015-11-20|website=Cabinet Secretariat Dept.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407183903/http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/5812015.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/M2032017.pdf|title=\u0930\u093e\u091c\u094d\u092f \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u0925\u093e \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092a\u0930\u093f\u0937\u0926 \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u0926\u0938\u094d\u092f \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0930\u0939\u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092c\u0928\u094d\u0927 \u092e\u0947\u0902\u0964|last=|first=|date=2017-07-27|website=Cabinet Secretariat Dept.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407184422/http://csd.bih.nic.in/Upload/Circulars/M2032017.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-08|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Currently, he is serving as Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Parsa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] since [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|2015]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/pdf/member_profile/121.pdf|title=Know your MLA|last=|first=|date=|website=Bihar Vidhan Sabha|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404193201/http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/pdf/member_profile/121.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-05|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHe quit the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] due to the marital dispute between his daughter and RJD president [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]'s son [[Tej Pratap Yadav]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/chandrika-rai-tej-pratap-yadavs-father-in-law-quits-rashtriya-janata-dal-2180362|title=Chandrika Rai, Tej Pratap's Father-In-Law, Quits Rashtriya Janata Dal|last=|first=|date=|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162600/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/chandrika-rai-tej-pratap-yadavs-father-in-law-quits-rashtriya-janata-dal-2180362|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/opinion/it-is-a-clash-of-stylish-titans-in-bihars-saran-as-rajiv-rudy-chandrika-rai-give-classy-twist-to-ls-battle-2126485.html|title=It is a Clash of \u2018Stylish\u2019 Titans in Bihar\u2019s Saran as Rajiv Rudy, Chandrika Rai Give Classy Twist to LS Battle|last=|first=|date=2019-05-03|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162749/https://www.news18.com/news/opinion/it-is-a-clash-of-stylish-titans-in-bihars-saran-as-rajiv-rudy-chandrika-rai-give-classy-twist-to-ls-battle-2126485.html|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life==\n\nChandrika Roy is the second son of the five sons of [[Daroga Prasad Rai]]. Chandrika Rai's daughter Aishwarya Rai married to [[Tej Pratap Yadav]], the eldest son of [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]] on 12 May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/aishwarya-rai-granddaughter-of-ex-bihar-cm-daroga-rai-to-marry-lalu-prasads-son-tej-pratap-yadav-5125826/|title=Aishwarya Rai, granddaughter of former Bihar CM Daroga Rai, to marry Lalu Prasad\u2019s son Tej Pratap Yadav|last=|first=|date=2018-04-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407162943/https://indianexpress.com/article/india/aishwarya-rai-granddaughter-of-ex-bihar-cm-daroga-rai-to-marry-lalu-prasads-son-tej-pratap-yadav-5125826/|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Tributes-paid-to-Daroga-Prasad-Rai/articleshow/194090705.cms|title=Tributes paid to Daroga Prasad Rai {{!}} Patna News - Times of India|last=Sep 3|first=|last2=2001|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407163121/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Tributes-paid-to-Daroga-Prasad-Rai/articleshow/194090705.cms?referral=PM|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-07|last3=Ist|first3=00:41}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rai, Chandrika}}\n[[Category:Members of the Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 1985\u20131990]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 1990\u20131995]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs